emphasis.docTitle:
Two new species of
Dasybasis Macquart
from the Peruvian Andes of Cusco ( Diptera : Tabanidae : Diachlorini )

subSection.paragraph:
Tabanid flies are found in a wide range of habitats, including forests, grasslands, wetlands, and water bodies. They are distributed globally, with species found on every continent except Antarctica . Adult female tabanids are known for their painful and irritating bites, as many species feed on the blood of mammals, including humans, livestock, and wildlife. Most female tabanids require blood meals to develop and lay their eggs, whereas males typically feed on nectar. Besides being painful, tabanid bites in some cases can transmit diseases (
Baldacchino et al . 2014
).

Three subfamilies and nine tribes of horse flies are found in South America. The tabanid tribe Diachlorini ( Tabanidae , Tabaninae), the most diverse tribe in the family, occurs mostly in the Australasian and Neotropical regions. More than half of the species in the tribe occur in the Neotropical region, where 594 of the 1,205 species and 41 genera of 75 genera are Diachlorini ( Coscarón & Papavero 2009 ; tatus,
Henriques et al. 2012
).

